  <definition xml:id="def-sampling-distribution-proportion">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <em>sampling distribution of the proportion</em> describes the pattern that the sample proportions tend to follow when randomly drawn from a population.  This distribution has a mean, <m>p</m>, and a standard error (i.e. the standard deviation of the sample proportions), <m>\sigma_p=\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}</m>.  (The sample proportion is <m>\overline{p}=\frac{x}{n}</m>.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        (Donnelly 7.25)
      </p>
      <p>
        For a population with a proportion equal to 0.32, calculate the standard error of the proportion for the following sample sizes.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>n=35</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>\sigma_p = \sqrt{\frac{0.32(1-0.32)}{35}}\approx 0.0788</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>n=70</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>\sigma_p = \sqrt{\frac{0.32(1-0.32)}{70}}\approx 0.0558</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>n=105</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>\sigma_p = \sqrt{\frac{0.32(1-0.32)}{105}}\approx 0.0455</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>

  </exercise>



